---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Editorial Team | pedestrianaccidentcalc.com';
const description = 'Meet the editorial team behind pedestrianaccidentcalc.com — personal injury litigation specialists who review every page for accuracy.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>Every page on pedestrianaccidentcalc.com is written and reviewed by editors with direct experience in personal injury litigation, insurance claims, and pedestrian accident law. No page is published without editorial review, and no sponsored or paid content appears on this site.</p>

  <h2>Pedestrian Injury &amp; Personal Injury Litigation Practice</h2>
  <p>Our editorial team leads the editorial team and is responsible for the calculator methodology, pain and suffering multipliers, and all primary content on this site. This side of the team's background is in personal injury litigation support, with specific experience in pedestrian accident cases involving catastrophic injuries, comparative fault disputes, uninsured motorist coverage claims, and insurance company negotiation tactics. This side of the team reviews all methodology content and is the final editorial authority on the accuracy of the calculator's damage estimates and fault reduction logic.</p>
  <p>The multiplier structure and fault rules documented on the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a> reflect this team's analysis of documented settlement patterns in pedestrian accident litigation across comparative and contributory negligence jurisdictions.</p>

  <h2>Insurance Coverage &amp; Claims Practice</h2>
  <p>Our team also contributes to guide and FAQ content, specializing in auto insurance coverage analysis, uninsured and underinsured motorist claims, personal injury protection (PIP) coordination, and the insurance company claims process for pedestrian accident victims. This side of the team's background includes personal injury insurance claims analysis, providing the insurance-side perspective on how adjusters evaluate pedestrian accident claims, how UM/UIM claims are processed, and what documentation matters most in the settlement negotiation process.</p>

  <h2>Editorial Standards</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Primary source grounding:</strong> Factual claims about fault rules, insurance coverage requirements, and state-specific laws are sourced to primary authorities — state statutes, case law, and insurance regulations — not to secondary summaries.</li>
    <li><strong>Documented methodology:</strong> Calculator multipliers and fault reduction logic are documented in full on the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>No sponsored content:</strong> Our editorial content — guides, methodology, and reviews — is monetized through Google AdSense display advertising only, with no sponsored articles or paid placements. Separately, the homepage offers an optional case-review form that is a disclosed paid attorney referral, unrelated to editorial content; see our <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a> for details.</li>
    <li><strong>Currency:</strong> Pages are reviewed and updated when relevant state laws or insurance regulations change.</li>
    <li><strong>Scope clarity:</strong> This site provides informational content only — not legal advice or case-specific predictions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Corrections Policy</h2>
  <p>If you identify a factual error — an incorrect state fault rule, an outdated insurance minimum, a multiplier that does not match documented settlement patterns — email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. Include the specific claim and the source you believe is more accurate. Corrections are reviewed within five business days.</p>

  <p>Return to the <a href="/">calculator</a> or see the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
